Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: occupational name, status name from Middle English  <i>king</i> ‘king’ + the genitival inflection  <i>-(e)s-</i> +  <i>man(n)</i> ‘man’, denoting one who had commended his services to the king and not to some baron. Compare Walter Kingesbonde, 1205 in   Pipe Rolls   (Northumb), Godwin Kingesreive, 1208 in   Feet of Fines   (Lincs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Pipe Rolls","meanings":["English: relationship name from the Middle English pet name  <i>Hercok</i>, a compound of  <i>Her</i> (a short form of  <i>Herbert</i> or  <i>Herman</i>) + the hypocoristic element  <i>cock</i>. Compare Here (Herbertus in   Pipe Roll, Chancellor’s Copy  ) de Oxhei, 1230 in   Pipe Rolls   (Herts)."]},{"name":"Feet of Fines","meanings":["Cornish, English: (i) possibly a locative name from Appledore (Devon), recorded as  <i>Surapple</i> in the early Middle Ages (12th-century Charter Rolls, copied in 1329), and as the fuller  <i>Sureapeldor</i>, 1242,  <i>Sourappeldore</i>, 1303 in   Place-Names of Devon  , meaning ‘sour-apple (crab-apple) tree’. The shorter name may have persisted in local speech into the surnaming period. (ii) possibly sometimes a nickname from Middle English  <i>sour</i> ‘sour’ +  <i>appel</i> ‘apple’; compare Joh. Sourappill, 1386 in   Feet of Fines   (Yorks)."]},{"name":"Kingman","meanings":["English (southeastern): occupational name from Middle English <i>king</i> ‘king’ + <i>man(n)</i> ‘man’, denoting a servant of the king, a member of the king's household."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Kingsman was born in 1508, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1508–":"1508–Surnud","1528–1583":"1528–1583","1508–Male":"1508–Surnud","1583":"1583","1508":"1508","1528":"1528","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1508–":"1508–Kuollut","1528–1583":"1528–1583","1508–Male":"1508–Kuollut","1583":"1583","1508":"1508","1528":"1528","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1508–":"1508–Décédé","1528–1583":"1528–1583","1508–Male":"1508–Décédé","1583":"1583","1508":"1508","1528":"1528","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Robert Kingsman est né en 1508, à Wiltshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1508–":"1508–Verstorben","1528–1583":"1528–1583","1508–Male":"1508–Verstorben","1583":"1583","1508":"1508","1528":"1528","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Robert Kingsman wurde 1508 in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"1508–":"1508–Desede","1528–1583":"1528–1583","1508–Male":"1508–Desede","1583":"1583","1508":"1508","1528":"1528","Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wiltshire, Angletè, United Kingdom"},"hu":{"1508–":"1508–elhunyt","1528–1583":"1528–1583","1508–Male":"1508–elhunyt","1